Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania-Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He hated it especially because he was responsible for waking up everyone else in his platoon. Quietly, he got up from his cot, put on his combat suit, threw his body armor over it, and took his things out of the locker, being careful with a certain small box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Everything he needed hung there, like his breathing apparatus or his special goggles. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barrack. Outside, mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He pulled a lighter out of one jacket pocket and a cigarette out of the other. He lit it and took a short drag before opening the door a little. In the last week, he had to come up with quite a few things to wake up the men and women under his command. He no longer used the preset alarm clock, because it usually didn't work and only a slight noise came out of the speakers.
“Wake them up?” Cohren turned around and saw Platoon Leader Nemic approaching him.
"Yes," answered Cohren.
"What are you going to try this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith and a few others came towards him already fully geared up.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What woke you up then?" asked Cohren.
"Well, first of all, we didn't feel like waiting to see what you would come up with today again. And secondly, the assault troops, who are the first to get up, are allowed to choose their morning ration," replied one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good argument, corporal," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a button. A loud, shrill alarm echoed through the barracks. Inside, he heard muffled cursing and people running around in a panic.
"Come on, Valturi," said Nemic. "One would think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
"Well, my people from the training camp have learned it," replied Cohren and pointed to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the platoon and company leaders also know that they have to get up before their units."
Seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal items to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, others more annoyed.
"Good morning," said Cohren in a good mood.
"With all due respect, Sir, why do you have to wake us up like that?" asked a sergeant from the assault troops.
"Because the regular alarms are crap and because Daybreak doesn't oversleep," said Cohren.
"Pack all your personal belongings," Cohren continued. As a lieutenant colonel and executive officer of the company, he was responsible for supervising and supporting them together with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be coming back here. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack your daily rations."
The members of the Exodus Company quickly dispersed. They were part of the second assault troop division, second army. Before they were combined, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked side by side in the glow of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward operating base. Most had red-tinted glass to avoid being spotted by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild-Weasel attacks in the air and on the ground to combat them.
"A new day and a new task for the Hellhounds," said Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"A forward operating base outside of Ianlos. We will support the ground attack," answered Cohren and took a drag on his cigarette. He gave Craith partial credit for starting him smoking, but a year in the field changed a person, so he said nothing.
"Shit. It's getting worse at the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news says: 'Support the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan Front.' How about help for the Howland Front?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren and flicked the remnants of his cigarette into the mud. "At least we're moving with the first armed platoon and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be there."
"Shaw made it clear we have a ride?" asked Nemic, a bit surprised.
"Yes. He's actually not so bad, as I thought. Not particularly friendly, but you can deal with him."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and put on his backpack at the same time. "All units of the Exodus Company will gather at the West Vehicle Park when they're done. We'll be departing with the first armed platoon at 0500."
He received immediate responses from the squad leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking corporals when they all came here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren had the feeling he had known them for ages, even though it had been at most two years. They were squad leaders, although Craith had been leading the second platoon for a week now, after its previous leader had been discharged for medical reasons following being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
On the way to the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four armored fighting vehicles. Their crews were running around, making sure their machines were combat-ready. Cohren quickly spotted Major Boradin Shaw, who was talking to the commander of the armed platoon. As they approached, Shaw looked over to them and came toward them, as always with an expressionless face.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said, Cohren was slower, while he looked at Cohren's pistol holster and then looked up again. "The company is ready, I assume?"
